| 1906 || || Legislation || || The Immigration Act of 1906 is passed. The Act is developed under the guidance of Frank Oliver, minister of the interior from 1905 to 1911, and a critic of unrestricted European immigration. The Act significantly expands the class of "undesirable" immigrants from the orginal specifications in 1869. It also formalizes the deportation process for people who would be denied entry, allowing for any person who wuld be denied entry to be deportable within two years of entering Canada. The Act also establishes boards of inquiry at each port to decide cases of immigrants seeking entry.<ref name=pier21-immigration-act-1906>{{cite web|url = https://www.pier21.ca/research/immigration-history/immigration-act-1906|title = Immigration Act, 1906|title = Immigration Act, 1906|accessdate = November 24, 2017|publisher = Canada Museum of Immigration at Pier21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://immigrationtous.net/140-immigration-act-canada-1906.html|title = IMMIGRATION ACT (CANADA) (1906)|accessdate = November 20, 2017|publisher = Immigration to North America}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url = https://journals.library.ualberta.ca/pi/index.php/pi/article/download/1415/958|title = "A brake upon the wheel": Frank Oliver and the Creation of the Immigration Act of 1906|last = Hollihan|first = K. Tony|journal = Past Imperfect|pages = 93-112|volume = 1|year = 1992|accessdate = November 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=canada-immigration-policy-1896-1910/><ref name=pier21/><ref name=passagetocanada/>
|-
| 1908 || || Agreement || || Gentlemen's Agreement, 1908.<ref name=pier21/> This is after negotiations began in 1907.<ref name=passagetocanada/>
|-
| 1908 || || Legislation || || The government of Canada passes the {{w|continuous journey regulation}}, an amendment to the Immigration Act of 1906 that forbids the entry of people who did not come from their country of birth or citizenship via a continuous journey. This is an attempt to indirectly block immigration from India and, to a lesser extent, Japan.<ref name=pier21-cjr>{{cite web|url = https://www.pier21.ca/research/immigration-history/continuous-journey-regulation-1908|title = Continuous Journey Regulation, 1908|accessdate = November 24, 2017|publisher = Canada Museum of Immigration at Pier21}}</ref><ref name=pier21/><ref name=passagetocanada/>
|-
| 1910 || || Legislation || || The Immigration Act of 1910 is passed. The Act reinforces and expands upon the provisions of the Immigration Act of 1906.<ref name=pier21-immigration-act-1910>{{cite web|url = https://www.pier21.ca/research/immigration-history/immigration-act-1910|title = Immigration Act, 1910|accessdate = November 24, 2017|publisher = Canada Museum of Immigration at Pier21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://blogs.ubc.ca/rajinsidhu/2015/03/06/3-1-immigration-act-1910/|title = 3.1 Immigration Act 1910|date = March 6, 2015|accessdate = November 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=eugenicsarchive>{{cite web|url = http://eugenicsarchive.ca/discover/timeline/5495c2414dcf0b0000000001|publisher = Eugenics Archive|accessdate = November 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=canada-immigration-policy-1896-1910>{{cite journal|url = https://www.jstor.org/stable/138931|title = Canada's Immigration Policy, 1896-1910|journal = The Canadian Journal of Economics and Political Science|volume = 26|number = 4|date = November 1, 1960|accessdate = November 24, 2017}}</ref>
